As of the [[census]]<ref name="GR2" /> of 2000, 25,233 people, 8,155 households, and 5,463 families resided in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,320.4 people per square mile (509.8/km<U+00B2>). There were 9,865 housing units, at an average density of 516.2 per square mile (199.3/km<U+00B2>). The racial makeup of the city was 76.69% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 5.31% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.59% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.63% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.02% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 14.41% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.35% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]]s or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]]s of any race were 44.64% of the population.

Of the 8,155 households, 32.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.3% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 14.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.0% were not families. About 29.2% of all households were made up of individuals, and 14.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.51, and the average family size was 3.10.

In the city, the population was distributed as 23.6% under the age of 18, 9.9% from 18 to 24, 32.7% from 25 to 44, 19.7% from 45 to 64, and 14.1% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females, there were 125.2 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 132.3 males.

The median income for a household in the city was $28,257, and for a family was $35,448. Males had a median income of $27,636 versus $21,863 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $14,119. About 17.1% of families and 22.2% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 30.0% of those under age 18 and 18.3% of those age 65 or over.

==Government and infrastructure==
[[File:Scenic Mountain Medical Center Big Spring Texas May 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Scenic Mountain Medical Center serves the community.]]
The [[Texas Department of Criminal Justice]] operates the Big Spring District Parole Office in the city.<ref>"[http://www.tdcj.state.tx.us/parole/parole-directory/paroledir-rgnldisparoff5.htm Parole Division Region V]." [[Texas Department of Criminal Justice]]. Retrieved on May 22, 2010.</ref>

The [[Texas Department of State Health Services]] operates a 200-bed psychiatric hospital, opened in 1939. The hospital has reduced its number of beds over the years, but remains one of the largest employers in Big Spring.

The [[United States Postal Service]] operates the Big Spring Post Office.<ref>"[http://usps.whitepages.com/service/post_office/big-spring-501-s-main-st-big-spring-tx-1354936 Post Office Location - BIG SPRING]." [[United States Postal Service]]. Retrieved on May 22, 2010.</ref>

The [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] (BOP) operates the [[Federal Correctional Institution, Big Spring]] in Big Spring.<ref>"[http://www.bop.gov/DataSource/execute/dsFacilityAddressLoc?start=y&facilityCode=big FCI Big Spring, Contact Information]." [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]. Retrieved on May 22, 2010.</ref> The nearby Big Spring Correctional Center is privately operated ([[GEO Group]]) on behalf of the BOP.<ref>"[http://www.bop.gov/DataSource/execute/dsFacilityAddressLoc?start=y&facilityCode=BSC CI Big Spring Contact Information]." [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]. Retrieved on May 22, 2010.</ref><ref>"[http://www.geogroup.com/Maps/LocationDetails/20]." [[GEO Group]]. Retrieved on July 25, 2013.</ref>

Following the 2011 redistricting, Howard County is represented in the [[Texas House of Representatives]] by the District 72 [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Drew Darby]] of [[San Angelo, Texas|San Angelo]].

The [[Colorado River Municipal Water District]] operates a [[reclaimed water]] treatment plant in Big Spring, the first of its kind in Texas, the product of which is then delivered to the potable water treatment plants of Big Spring, Stanton, Midland, and [[Odessa, Texas|Odessa]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mybigspring.com/water_treatment |title= Water Treatment Plant |date= |website= Big Spring, Texas |publisher= City of Big Spring |access-date= 2015-03-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.watereuse.org/node/3300 |title= Foundation Partners with Carollo Engineers on Innovative Research |date= |website= |publisher= [[WateReuse]] |access-date= 2015-03-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.watereuse.org/node/3300 |title= Testing Water Quality in a Municipal Wastewater Effluent Treated to Drinking Water Standards |date= |website= |publisher= [[Texas Water Development Board]] |access-date= 2015-03-08 }}</ref>

==Culture==
Big Spring is the site of several major [[hang gliding]] championship tournaments, including the U.S. [[Hang Gliding]] Nationals.<ref>http://www.ushpa.aero/news.asp?id=136</ref> The city was also the site for the filming of parts of ''Midnight Cowboy'' and ''[[Hangar 18 (film)|Hangar 18]]''.<ref>http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0080836/</ref>

The Big Spring Heritage [[Museum]] contains pioneer and [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indian]] [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]], art exhibits, and the largest collection known of [[Texas Longhorn (cattle)|Texas Longhorn]] [[Cattle#Terminology|steer]] horns. Its rare and unusual [[phonograph]]s include models by [[Thomas A. Edison]]. It also houses a large collection of [[doll]]s. The museum is located at 510 Scurry; an admission fee is charged.<ref>Texas Transportation Commission, ''Texas State Travel Guide, 2007'', p. 111</ref>

==Notable people==
*[[Larry Arnhart]], a writer and scholar, graduated from Big Spring High School in 1967.
*[[Carl Bunch]] was the drummer for [[Buddy Holly]] during the "Winter Dance Party" tour in 1959 in which Holly died ([[the Day the Music Died]]), and later for [[Hank Williams, Jr.]] and [[Roy Orbison]].
*[[Betty Buckley]] is a Tony Award-winning American  theater, film, and television actress and singer.
*[[Putt Choate]] - [[NFL]] player for the [[Green Bay Packers]].
*[[Mike Christie (ice hockey)]] - [[NHL]] player for the [[California Seals]] and [[Cleveland Barons (NHL)|Cleveland Barons]].
*[[Bubba Franks]], a former [[National Football League]] [[tight end]] for the [[Green Bay Packers]], was born in [[California]], but was raised and played [[high school]] [[American football|football]] in Big Spring.<ref>[http://www.packers.com/draft/2000/franks/ Daniel "Bubba" Franks bio (2000 NFL draft preview)] on [http://www.packers.com packers.com], the official website of the Green Bay Packers</ref>
*[[J. J. Pickle]] - [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] from the [[United States House of Representatives, Texas District 10|10th congressional district]] of [[Texas]] from 1963&mdash;1995
*[[Stephan Pyles]] - creator of New Texas Cuisine and a founding father of ''haute'' Southwestern cuisine
*[[Tony Franklin (placekicker)]] played for the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], [[New England Patriots]], and [[Miami Dolphins]]; this barefoot kicker set 18 NCAA records playing at Texas A&M, led the NFL in scoring (140 points) and field goals made (32) in 1986, and was selected to represent the AFC in the Pro Bowl. He played in [[Super Bowl XV]] and [[Super Bowl XX]].
*[[J. T. Smith (American football)|J. T. Smith]], wide receiver for the St. Louis and Phoenix Cardinals, Washington Redskins and Kansas City Chiefs, played 13 years in the NFL, then coached the San Angelo indoor team. He played at North Texas State after finishing at Big Spring High School. He was inducted to the Big Spring Hall of Fame in 2002. JT was named to the AFC Pro Bowl team in 1980 and the NFC Pro Bowl team in 1988. He also led the NFL in total punt returns in 1979 and 1980.
*[[Tom Sorley]] <U+2014> President/CEO of Rosendin Electric
*[[Jesse Whittenton]], NFL player for the [[Los Angeles Rams]] and Green Bay Packers, was a member of the 1961 and 1962 NFL Champion Packers.
*[[Ryan Tannehill]], quarterback and wide receiver for the [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M Aggies]], was drafted by the Miami Dolphins in the first round (eighth overall pick) of the 2012 NFL Draft.

